1988</i>.<br><a name="fn142" href="#fnB142">[139]</a><i> Human Rights Act 1993
</i>(NZ)<i> </i>s 22(1)(a); <i>Human Rights Commission v Eric Sides Motor Co Ltd
</i> <a href="/cgi-bin/LawCite?cit=%281981%29%202%20NZAR%20443" title="View LawCiteRecord" class="autolink_findcases">(1981) 2 NZAR 443 (EOT).</a><br><a name="fn143" href="#fnB143">[140]</a>
<i>Human Rights Act 1993</i> (NZ) ss 22 and
28(1).<br><a name="fn144" href="#fnB144">[141]</a> Namely a belief in a
supernatural being, thing, or principal, and the acceptance of canons of conduct
in order to give effect to
that belief: <i>Centrepoint Community Growth Trust v
Commissioner of Inland Revenue </i> <a href="/cgi-bin/LawCite?cit=%5b1985%5d%201%20NZLR%20673" title="View LawCiteRecord" class="autolink_findcases">[1985] 1 NZLR 673</a>, applying <i>Church of the
New Faith v Commissioner for Pay-roll Tax (Victoria) </i><a href="http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/cases/cth/HCA/1983/40.html" title="View Case" class="autolink_findcases_inserted">[1983] HCA 40</a>;  <a href="/cgi-bin/LawCite?cit=%281983%29%20154%20CLR%20120" title="View LawCiteRecord" class="autolink_findcases">(1983) 154 CLR 120
(Mason</a> ACJ and Brennan J).<br><a name="fn145" href="#fnB145">[142]</a> Which
definition includes a person who is for the time-being exercising functions
analogous to those of a minister of religion; <i>Evidence Act 1908 </i>(NZ) s 2-
